On the strength of this statement two opposite theo- ries have been founded τ

(i) By Macleane, who takes the words to mean that our Sixth Satire is incomplete, and adds that line 75 ‘begins a new branch of the subject, which is left un- finished3'

(ii) By Jahn, who admits the incompleteness of the Satires as a whole but regards the Sixth as complete in its present form.
